     <int-org-section id="ITUC.IO.32" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
          <heading>Activities</heading>
          <p>The ITUC has designated the following as cross-sector `frontline’ issues: Democracies for People (`Fighting for Democracy’ was declared by the General Council in December 2023 to be ITUC’s priority theme for 2024); A New Social Contract for Recovery and Resilience (in November 2022 the fifth ITUC World Congress issued a Statement on a New Social Contract between workers, governments and businesses, with a focus on advancing Jobs; Rights; Wages; Social Protection; Equality; and Inclusion); and Climate- and Employment-Proof Our Work with Just Transition (the need for `just transition of the workforce and the creation of decent work and quality jobs’ is enshrined in the 2015 Paris Agreement on climate change, in relation to technological advancements and shifts in energy developed in the context of adapting to and mitigating the impacts of climate change). The ITUC’s activities are focused around four pillars:</p>
          <p-group>
               <heading>Peace, Democracy and Rights</heading>
               <p>
        The ITUC’s Peace, Democracy and Rights pillar has three thematic areas: Peace and Disarmament, Countries at Risk, and Migration and Slavery. In April 2022 the ITUC, with the 
        <xr pageref="N" ref="WB0231XD.IO.TXT.28">International Peace Bureau</xr>
         and Sweden’s Olof Palme Center, released 
        <publ-name>For Our Shared Future,</publ-name>
         detailing recommendations on strengthening common global security; these emphasized the need for, 
        <i>inter alia,</i>
         global and regional co-operation, multilateralism, rule of law, dialogue and responsible governance. In November the ITUC issued 
        <publ-name>Freedom Report 2022: Unions Building Peace</publ-name>
        , which emphasized the critical role played by trade unions in combating authoritarianism, oppression, conflict and exclusion. Also in November, the fifth ITUC World Congress adopted emergency resolutions that condemned the Russian Federation’s (Belarus-assisted) invasion of Ukraine; stated solidarity with pro-women’s rights protesters in Iran; and focused on the need to combat far-right extremist ideologies. 
      </p>
               <p>
        The ITUC prepares an annual Global Rights Index. The 10th edition, released in June 2023, measured the protection of workers’ rights in 163 countries during 2022, with regard to 97 internationally recognized indicators. It found that the right to strike had been violated in 87% of countries (compared with 63% in 2014), the right to engage in collective bargaining had been denied for certain or all workers in 79%, and freedom of assembly and free speech had been denied or constrained in 42%. Moreover, workers had been prohibited from establishing or joining a trade union in 77% of countries (particularly affected were platform workers—for example certain delivery drivers, temporary workers, migrant workers, domestic workers, and workers in the informal economy and in special economic zones). The Index rated countries in five bandings, ranging from no guarantee of rights, through systemic, regular or repeated violations of rights, to (the best category) sporadic violations of rights. The 10 countries most actively repressive to workers’ rights were reported to be Bangladesh, Belarus, Ecuador, Egypt, Eswatini, Guatemala, Myanmar, the Philippines, Tunisia and Türkiye. Workers had been exposed to violence in 44 countries in 2022, and trade unionists were reported to have been murdered during that year in Brazil, Colombia, Ecuador, El Salvador, Eswatini, Guatemala, Peru and Sierra Leone. The ITUC supports ratification of the 
        <xr pageref="N" ref="IO-UN.2077">International Labour Organization (ILO)’s</xr>
         Convention 
        
        No. 190, which aims to eliminate violence and harassment in the work place. The ITUC also advocates for fair recruitment of migrant workers and for the end of bonded labour systems (modern slavery) and child labour.
      </p>
               <!--3 reports issued in xii.24 relating to experiences of migrant workers and returnees. Support for planned Int Conventon on Business and Human Rights-->
          </p-group>
          <p-group>
               <heading>Regulating Economic Power</heading>
               <p>Under this pillar the ITUC focuses on corporate power; multilateralism; jobs; and shared prosperity. Issues addressed include combating the impacts on the labour market of global corporations (such as the prevalence of informal precarious labour contracts); developing appropriate taxation systems; improving public services and social protection systems; and formulating global standards relating to platform businesses (a business model that facilitates exchanges between two or more independent groups, and hitherto has notably evaded national legislation and taxation), and relating to data management (with a focus on privacy and surveillance protections).</p>
               <p>In November 2022 the fifth ITUC World Congress reported that more than 250m. jobs had been lost owing to impacts of the COVID-19 pandemic crisis, and that levels of underemployment had worsened in many countries. The Congress demanded that by 2030 575m. new jobs should be created globally, and one-half of all informal jobs should be formalized. </p>
          </p-group>
          <p-group>
               <heading>Equality</heading>
               <p>
        The ITUC opposes discrimination, marginalization and exclusion on the basis of, 
        <i>inter alia,</i>
         class, age, ethnicity, gender identity, disability and migration status, and emphasizes that the intersection of these characteristics pervades the world of work. The ITUC promotes women’s leadership, and notes the high global gender pay gap (detrimental to women), as well as the high share of unpaid care work undertaken by women. It has advocated for universal access to free, high-quality public healthcare and for a Global Fund for Universal Social Protection. In February 2024 the ITUC joined the Global Coalition for Social Justice (an initiative of the 
        <xr pageref="N" ref="IO-UN.2077">ILO</xr>
        ). 
      </p>
               <p usage="edio">The ITUC supports International Equal Pay Day, observed annually on 18 September.</p>
          </p-group>
          <p-group>
               <heading>Global Shifts—Just Transitions</heading>
               <p>
        This focuses on the thematic areas of climate and future of work. The Just Transition Centre, established in 2016, by the ITUC with other partners, promote social dialogue in planning a low-carbon future agenda. The ITUC urges all employers to develop plans that climate-proof their operations, and encourages all governments to develop, with the involvement of trade unions at all levels, `Just Transition’ measures that address, and protect workers and communities from, the onwards impacts of climate change. Furthermore, the ITUC focuses on the impacts of technology (such as digitalization, automation and data collection) on job opportunities and on supply chains. In November 2022 the fifth ITUC World Congress demanded that regulatory frameworks ensure decent working conditions for remote workers. In February 2023 a report commissioned by the ITUC, 
        <publ-name>Algorithmic transparency and accountability in the world of work</publ-name>
        , focused on means of addressing risks arising from automation in the workplace. The ITUC advocated for and welcomed the inclusion of references to labour rights and social protection in a Just Transitions Work Programme that was agreed by the 28th Conference of the Parties to the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change, held in Dubai, United Arab Emirates.
      </p>
          </p-group>
          <p-group>
               <heading usage="edio">Council of Global Unions</heading>
               <p usage="edio">In November 2006, following its establishment, the ITUC ratified an agreement with the Global Unions (global trade union federations) and the Trade Union Advisory Committee to the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development to form a Council of Global Unions, which meets annually. Since 2007 representatives of ITUC regional organizations, Global Unions, and affiliated trade union organizations have participated in a Trade Union Development Cooperation Network.</p>
          </p-group>
     </int-org-section>
     <int-org-section id="ICFTU.IO.115" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
          <heading>Finance</heading>
          <p id="ICFTU.IO.90">Affiliated organizations pay an affiliation fee per 1,000 members per annum, which contributes, with external donations and other resources, to financing the ITUC’s activities. The Confederation’s total expenditure in 2024 was forecast at €20.4m., of which affiliation fees were to provide €13.7m.</p>
