                    <org-entry-head>
                         <org-entry-name>International Federation of Journalists (IFJ)</org-entry-name>
                    </org-entry-head>
                    <address-block>
                         <address type="POSTAL">
                              <verbatim-address>International Press Centre, 155 rue de la Loi, 1040 Brussels, Belgium</verbatim-address>
                         </address>
                         <telephone alsofax="N">(2) 235-22-00</telephone>
                         <fax>(2) 235-22-19</fax>
                         <email>ifj@ifj.org</email>
                         <internet>www.ifj.org</internet>
                    </address-block>
                    <found-date>1952</found-date>
                    <content-note style="NORMAL">promotes social justice, human rights, democracy and pluralism</content-note>
                    <content-note style="NORMAL">it conducts surveys, assists in trade union training programmes, organizes seminars and provides information; it arranges fact-finding missions in countries where press freedom is under pressure, and issues protests against the persecution and detention of journalists and against media censorship; holds Congress every 3 years (2022: Oman, in late May-early June)</content-note>
                    <content-note style="NORMAL">in Aug. 2021 the IFJ condemned a decision by the Belarus Supreme Court to dissolve the Belarusian Association of Journalists (BAJ), an independent org. representing the rights of media workers in that country; in March 2023 the IFJ stated solidarity with the BAJ membership following its designation at the end of Feb. by the Belarus regime as an `extremist group’</content-note>
                    <content-note style="NORMAL">at the end of 2023 the IFJ reported that, worldwide, 120 journalists and media personnel had been killed during the year in work-related incidents</content-note>
                    <content-note style="NORMAL">the IFJ observed 26 Feb. 2024 as the International Day of Palestinian Journalists, at which time it reported that at least 100 journalists and media workers had been killed in Gaza since the massive escalation of Hamas-Israel conflict on 7 Oct. 2023, terming this `a massacre’</content-note>
                    <stats>mems: 187 unions in more than 140 countries, comprising 600,000 individuals</stats>
